&gt;&gt; Peter A Bleed wrote:
&gt;&gt;     
&gt;&gt;&gt; Enore,
&gt;&gt;&gt; I want to second Gordon&#39;s advice. I would urge you not to alter 
&gt;&gt;&gt;       
&gt; your  sword
&gt;   
&gt;&gt;&gt; in the way you are describing. If you want a grooved blade order 
&gt;&gt;&gt;       
&gt; one or
&gt;   
&gt;&gt;&gt; find one. At the very least you should not do anything until you 
&gt;&gt;&gt;       
&gt; have had
&gt;   
&gt;&gt;&gt; your blade well shinsa&#39;d.
&gt;&gt;&gt; Still, your question does point up a basic feature of the world of
&gt;&gt;&gt; nippon-to. The values and standards of the various people 
&gt;&gt;&gt;       
&gt; involved in
&gt;   
&gt;&gt;&gt; Japanese swords are diverse. What is absolutely &quot;wrong&quot; to some 
&gt;&gt;&gt;       
&gt; is &quot;just
&gt;   
&gt;&gt;&gt; fine&quot; to others. Most of us base our actions on our views of 
&gt;&gt;&gt;       
&gt; aesthetics and
&gt;   
&gt;&gt;&gt; a sense of historical preservation. There are other values out 
&gt;&gt;&gt;       
&gt; there and
&gt;   
&gt;&gt;&gt; knowing that helps to understand some of the things we see about 
&gt;&gt;&gt;       
&gt; swords.
&gt;   
&gt;&gt;&gt; When I was first in Japan I happened to meet a number of sword 
&gt;&gt;&gt;       
&gt; craftsmen
&gt;   
&gt;&gt;&gt; rather than collectors. Of course this was interesting (heck, it 
&gt;&gt;&gt;       
&gt; was
&gt;   
&gt;&gt;&gt; wonderful), but it may have given me a skewed view.
&gt;&gt;&gt; 1. The first &quot;smith&quot; I met ( and he was an important artist-and a
&gt;&gt;&gt; wonderful person) was re-tempering some old swords when I visited 
&gt;&gt;&gt;       
&gt; his
&gt;   
&gt;&gt;&gt; forge.
&gt;&gt;&gt; 2.  An important kinko proudly showed me his portfolio that 
&gt;&gt;&gt;       
&gt; included some
&gt;   
&gt;&gt;&gt; very excellent &quot;umegane&quot; work he had done. He assured me that &quot;no 
&gt;&gt;&gt;       
&gt; one could
&gt;   
&gt;&gt;&gt; see&quot; the fillings he had put into some seriously flawed blades.
&gt;&gt;&gt; 3. During a road trip with a fellow who had recently completed his
&gt;&gt;&gt; polishing apprenticeship, we took a long extra trip to let his 
&gt;&gt;&gt;       
&gt; teacher see
&gt;   
&gt;&gt;&gt; the grooves he was carving on a tanto. He was proud of his work 
&gt;&gt;&gt;       
&gt; and his
&gt;   
&gt;&gt;&gt; master approved. When I asked why he was doing it, he said &quot;the 
&gt;&gt;&gt;       
&gt; smith
&gt;   
&gt;&gt;&gt; should have put the grooves in.&quot;
&gt;&gt;&gt; These men are not crooks or villains. Indeed, I think they are 
&gt;&gt;&gt;       
&gt; great
&gt;   
&gt;&gt;&gt; artists and skilled students, but they operate with a different 
&gt;&gt;&gt;       
&gt; set of
&gt;   
&gt;&gt;&gt; values.
&gt;&gt;&gt; You certainly can find craftsmen who will do what you ask of 
&gt;&gt;&gt;       
&gt; them, but one
&gt;   
&gt;&gt;&gt; thing is clear. You will only be able to cut grooves in your 
&gt;&gt;&gt;       
&gt; sword once. I
&gt;   
&gt;&gt;&gt; urge you to proceed with caution.
&gt;&gt;&gt; Peter
